recordings.loc: Burt Township (near  Shingleton), Alger County, Michigan (Adams Trail near H58)
recordings.rmk: Bird was photographed while it was calling from a tree top, among dense foliage, alongside the gravel road that is Adams Trail. At one point, its voice becomes softer on the recording, when the bird moved out of sight temporarily. Its call is slightly reminiscent of a Least Flycatcher. Since this call is not often recorded, I searched eBird for other examples, and found Jay McGowan's ML175638101, recorded in New York on 8/29/19.  This suggests the call may be associated with migration. There were other Red-eyed Vireos in the tree also.

recordings.loc: Burt Township (near  Seney), Alger County, Michigan (Adams Trail)
recordings.rmk: Bird was singing loudly from about 7 meters up in a maple tree that overhung the road, moving around as it foraged.  Phrases are very musical and complex, not repetitive, and not burry. Breast color was pale yellow along the sides/flanks, white centrally.  Several vireos were in the vicinity, but I did not see any interaction between this bird and the others.

recordings.rmk:
The recording was not modified. 

The habitat is a mature, aspen forest, with some birch. Hazelnut bush is in the understory. The weather was warm, calm winds, and sunny. The main song seems to be like a Warbling vireo. However, there are two sharp notes at the end of its song which confuses me. An example is at 19 sec in the recording.

Here are the key words about this recording: American Crow, American Redstart, birds, Breeding Season (Jun-Jul), Hazelton, mystery bird, Warbling vireo.

Thank-you for your interest,
Larry at Hazelton, BC, Canada

recordings.loc: Village Point Preserve, Daphne, Baldwin County, Alabama
recordings.rmk:
Recording unedited.
Bird in hardwoods singing from well up in a tree.
Did not see anything that should have affected the bird's behavior.  This location is just a few miles south of the southernmost regular breeding Red-eyed Vireos.

A Red-eyed Vireo in the same location a day before intrigued me by occasionally giving a level pip-pip-pip-pip-pip in the middle of a series of typical Red-eyed Vireo phrases.  Today this bird did the same.  The pip-pip-pip-pip-pip phrase can be heard early on and then near the end of the recording
